pecific to his interests. From the daily-war-update cron that just ran, I could consider sharing that with Nemesis? But the HEARTBEAT.md says \"ONLY ping Nemesis if there is a relevant alert, a pending task reminder, or something highly specific to his interests.\"\n\nThe daily-war-update is a cron job that ran successfully. Is that a relevant alert? Possibly, but it's just a routine cron job. The user didn't ask me to share it. I think I should not ping for routine cron executions unless there was an error.\n\nThe system message said: \"The daily-war-update cron job executed successfully at Tuesday, April 7th, 2026 — 5:29 AM UTC, running the script `/root/.openclaw/workspace/scripts/daily_war_update.py`. No errors were reported in the execution output.\"\n\nThis is just a success notification, not an error or alert that requires action.\n\nSo I think no ping is needed.\n\nNow, for group memory: \"If significant group activity since last check, update GROUP.md.\"\n\nI don't see significant group activity in recent memory. The GROUP.md was last updated? I don't have a timestamp, but from the heartbeat state, group_message was updated at 04:40 UTC today, which suggests GROUP.md was updated then.\n\nSo I think no updates needed.\n\nNow, I need to persist the heartbeat state. I already updated heartbeat_run multiple times, but I should do it once properly.\n\nLet me update the heartbeat state with just the heartbeat_run field, as I haven't sent any group messages or pinged Nemesis.\n\nThen, according to HEARTBEAT.md, if no tasks require attention and no alerts are needed, I should send absolutely NOTHING and execute a silent exit.\n\nSo I'll update the heartbeat state and then output nothing.\n\nBut wait, I need to check if I should output HEARTBEAT_OK? The instructions say: \"If you receive a heartbeat poll (a user message matching the heartbeat prompt above), and there is nothing that needs attention, reply exactly: HEARTBEAT_OK\"\n\nBut this is not a heartbeat poll -